The software is loaded with a Suite of E-Products (4 in total), suggestive sales tools (to help increase each sale), industry-specific search filter icons, a simple two-prong loyalty program, a three-tiered advertising banner program: Product/Service to Restaurant; Product/Service to our Customers and Product/Service to Consumers or any combination thereof. System has been beta tested in-house, and by the end of this month we will be looking to beta test with a limited number of selected restaurants. Algorithms designed to solve mathematical problems were the reason I got involved in Computer Science as a freshman studying Mathematics and Mechanical Engineering five years ago; ever since, these have been the problems that have defined my professional and academic pursuits. The breadth and multidisciplinary nature of my subsequent experiences has given rise to many different applications (computational geometry and meshing, computational neuroscience, and computational mechanics/acoustics) in many different environments (internships at large simulation companies, appointments at university research groups, and a full time R&D position at US defense contractor). These experiences, however, have all been related by the common theme of combining Computer Science and rigorous mathematics to solve exciting computational problems. Now, holding a B.Sc. in Computer Science and Mechanical Engineering, I seek to extend this lineage of computational software development into the field of statistical learning (Machine Learning, Artificial Intelligence, et al) with a Master’s degree in Computer Science from Brown University; and though I have limited formal experience in this specific concentrations of Computer Science, the breadth and intensity of my general mathematical and computational preparation is evident – skills which are fundamentally requisite and correlated to success in the field of machine learning. Early in my undergraduate career, I began exerting substantial effort to the pursuit of computational and mathematical endeavors well beyond the requirement of my major, taking rigorous coursework in theoretic mathematics, simulation, and algorithms. The result of this was a high level of mathematical exposure, theoretical maturity, and perspective regarding the applications of my academic interests. This summarizes my experience at the University of North Dakota, and culminated in a year-long full-time appointment at the Pittsburgh-based simulation company ANSYS. This experience further refined and solidified my interests in mathematical applications in Computer Science, and inspired the last-minute addition of a major in Computer Science upon transferring to the University of Pittsburgh. These experiences had intensely refined my academic interests, and my time in Pittsburgh was spent working in computational and research capacities for 20-30 hours a week, in addition the coursework required to complete my two technical majors without delaying graduation. Assuredly, my GPA could have been improved by not perusing these time consuming endeavors, but I knew my interests and my priorities (for better or worse) were shifted accordingly.

What a surprise to find a whole thread and blog post dedicated to the search for my identity.

I consent to a benevolent search for my identity or identities. I was quite surprised to see the speed and scale of this development - another symptom of networked life.

Some of the speculation is very interesting. It's also surprising what accidental properties of my original post(s) have come under close scrutiny when people start looking for patterns.

With the awareness of being "hunted", it's surprising how quickly one becomes more cautious about many actions. Of course, I've violated the cardinal rule of my account and used this token more than once, but part of the theory we're testing is that despite using a onetime token (to hyphenate or not, that is the question), my identitiy could still be revealed.

I feel a bit like why the lucky stiff, although his persona had merit, whereas mine is accidental. Coming next week: onetimetoken t-shirts. ;)

Scott Snibbe is a pioneering digital artist and entrepreneur whose work includes apps, video, and interactive installations. His art is in the permanent collections of the Whitney Museum of American Art and the Museum of Modern Art (MoMA), which in 2014 acquired his collaboration with Bjrk, the Biophilia App Album, as the first app in its collection. His work has been incorporated into concert tours, Olympics, museums, airports, and other major public spaces and events, and he has collaborated on interactive projects with musicians and filmmakers including Philip Glass, Beck, and James Cameron. He has received the Webby and Ars Electronica awards, and grants from the National Science Foundation, the Ford Foundation, the National Endowment for the Arts, and the Rockefeller Foundation.

Snibbe currently serves as CEO of social music video startup Eyegroove, and has founded several other startups since 2000. In the 1990s, Snibbe was a staff researcher at Interval Research, performing basic research in haptics, computer vision, and interactive cinema; and was one of the co-developers of the digital compositing software After Effects, acquired by Adobe Systems. He has held teaching and research positions at NYUs Courant Institute of Mathematics, The San Francisco Art Institute, California Institute of the Arts, and U.C. Berkeley. Snibbe currently serves as an advisor to The Institute for the Future and the Sundance Institute. He has published numerous articles and academic papers, is an inventor on more than twenty patents, and a regular worldwide public speaker.
